        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1957-02-20T19:39:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1957-02-20T19:39:00-05:00" n="425"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d425">
                <head>425. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Laos</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d425fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 751J.00/2–2057. Secret. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_KE1"
                            >Kocher</persName> and cleared by <persName corresp="#p_CTJ1"
                            >Corcoran</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_SWJ1">Sebald</persName>.
                        Repeated to London, Paris, Saigon, Ottawa, Phnom Penh, New Delhi, and
                        Bangkok.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1957-02-20T19:39:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 20, 1957—7:39 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1044. Vientiane 1359.<note n="2" xml:id="d425fn2">In telegram 1359 from
                        Vientiane, February 20, the Embassy confirmed information which it had
                        tentatively reported in telegram 1351, February 19. The information was that
                            <persName corresp="#p_S1">Souphanouvong</persName> had asked <persName
                            corresp="#p_SP2">Souvanna Phouma</persName> to request economic aid from
                        the People’s Republic of China as evidence of Laos’ neutrality and in return
                        for Pathet Lao agreement to guarantees requested by the Royal Lao
                        Government. (<hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, 751G.00/2–2057 and
                        751–.00/2–1957, respectively)</note> Department assumes Lao Government and
                    leaders sufficiently aware acceptance <gloss target="#t_ChiCom1">ChiCom</gloss>
                    economic aid falls within purview November 13 letter and would probably result
                    in US reappraisal economic and political policy vis-à-vis Laos. If such not
                    case, however, at your discretion in contacts with Lao leaders you may wish at
                    appropriate times indicate that November 13 letter defining US policy also
                    applies to eventualities other than coalition government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
